    {
      "id": "41d8187a_bf0ccb84",
      "file_path": "kubernetes/oof/charts/oof-has/values.yaml",
      "patchset_number": 13,
      "line": 50,
      "message": "Yes this is the key thats used to encrypt the passwords.  In order to use secrets, this would require another code change.",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 2923,
        "name": "Vikas Varma",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "vikas.varma@att.com",
        "username": "vrvarma"
      },
      "updated": "2020-04-03 23:33:06.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": "9cdd527b_38addb94",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "id": "0cea3a87_7628b72e",
      "file_path": "kubernetes/oof/charts/oof-has/values.yaml",
      "patchset_number": 13,
      "line": 50,
      "message": "Then you have my -2 on this patch.\nThis is a bad design pattern and we are fighting with it so no new occurrences of such patter should be accepted.\nYou don't need to make code changes to use secrets. We have establish a pattern with the init container where everything happens transparently for the application. You can fine some example here:\nhttps://gerrit.onap.org/r/c/oom/+/104816\nhttps://gerrit.onap.org/r/c/oom/+/104817\nhttps://gerrit.onap.org/r/c/oom/+/101287\nhttps://gerrit.onap.org/r/c/oom/+/101937",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 4965,
        "name": "Krzysztof Opasiak",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "k.opasiak@samsung.com",
        "username": "kopasiak"
      },
      "updated": "2020-04-03 23:55:19.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": "41d8187a_bf0ccb84",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "id": "61c58ab1_9a4fb205",
      "file_path": "kubernetes/oof/charts/oof-has/values.yaml",
      "patchset_number": 13,
      "line": 50,
      "message": "alternatively if you *really* want those encrypted passwords you can have them but:\n1) Encryption key has to be generated (use common secret tamplate)\n2) all passwords should be in plain text in values.yaml file\n3) password encryption should happen in the init container not before the deployment (don't force your user to reencrypt all passwords manually as this would be a nightmare)",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 4965,
        "name": "Krzysztof Opasiak",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "k.opasiak@samsung.com",
        "username": "kopasiak"
      },
      "updated": "2020-04-04 00:03:12.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": "0cea3a87_7628b72e",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "id": "396edd56_f96a57eb",
